   >What I want to know is:
   >1) Why do CS majors here use Unix?  What is it that is so great about Unix
   >   that can't be done with OS/2?  No flames on this one.

   Unix is popular because it has been around for a good while and more
   significantly because much of it was written by hackers.

And also because of several features that OS/2 and NT do not have:

1) Remote graphical login. OS/2 and AFAIK NT have telnet daemons,
but they do not have X11. You cannot put several GUI users SIMULTANEOUSLY 
on OS/2 or NT box.

2) Multiuser capabilities: UIDs, access rigths, etc. (NT has it,
but NT also is much bigger and uglyer(sp?) than UNIX). This is important
when several users work on same computer. 

Also it is useful to "clusterise" single-user workstations - 
share parts of disk space. On OS/2 when you log in via telnet or NFS
you can see ALL disk. On UNIXes you will see only part of disk that
was allowed to see.

3) Good internal design. NT need 16 and more megs to do things that 
Linux does in 4!

   >2) Isn't the lack of "killer" apps a good reason not to use Unix?

It depends on what do you want to do. IMO large database managers like 
ORACLE or Informix are "killer" apps in UNIX world. There are
many industrial CADs for Sun/HP/DEC/etc, ways better than Autocad.

UNIX is just another computer market. If all you want to do is
text processing, small database or "electronic tables" Intel/MS Windows is
enought for you. (May be you could use OS/2 'cos it is better Windows
than MS one). If you  need large multiuser database you need UNIX and
ORACLE/Informix. If you need CAD, you need workstation - no other option
than UNIX. If you need hard real time you need some UNIXoid OS like QNX.
May be System V R4 will do. It is impossible to do realtime on OS/2 and NT.

So, Intel runing MS Windows|OS/2 is good enough for offices and may be for 
home use. Note, good enough does not mean it is GOOD. When you come
to serious applications, like industrial CADs or scientific research,
you hardly have other options than UNIX. Intels and MACs can be used
only as cheap graphical terminals.

   I don't think people use Unix for basic wordprocessing. There certainly
   is a dearth of decent X apps, probably because the only common API,
   Athena, is ugly (no 3D, 4 colours). Motif is prettier, but it isn't
   free. OpenLook, pretty, free, but hasn't caught on with the big
   companies (except Sun of course), probably for political reasons.

