   >4) Why do developers use Unix platforms to develop software?  Is it because
   >   of multitasking/crash protection/memory model?  Is it true that
   >   "everyone important in the industry is moving to Windows NT" ?  Why can't
   >   developers use something like the OS/2 environment to develop software?

Because UNIX has good and consistent(sp?) API. And this API is fully
functional. If you familiar with basic concepts of programming, like
multiprocessing and file I/O, you can learn to write useful programs
on UNIX in several minutes. X11 API is big, but AFAIK it is not much bigger
than MS Windows or PM. Also it is very easy to write device drivers
in UNIX (at least, in BSD).

To make UNIX application you should think awhile what you want to do, 
RTFM and write. For simple task it will take several minutes.

To make MS DOS or MS Windows application, you should think awhile,
browse bunch of manuals, hacker guides, "Undocumented Windows" books,
finally find that it is impossible to do what you want directly,
think awhile again to find a workaround and return to previous step.
You also have to do something special when you get adrenaline overflow.

The worst thing that there is a generation of hackers who think that
it is a normal way of software development.

Sorry, I never tried to write for OS/2 and not informed enough to
make an opinion.

